720730f-a.title: Manhattan: King Street - Varick Street
720730f-a.text:
84, 76-68 King Street, west of, adioining, and at the S.W. corner
of Varick Street. The clearing in the foreground is part of the
future site of the new United States Appraisers' Stores, a 1arge
building filling the entire block.
No. 84 King Street is a garage, built since 1921, and replacing
five old houses, Nos. 82 to 90 King Street.
December 7, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.

723764f-a.title: Manhattan: Varick Street - King Street
723764f-a.text:
Graphic Arts Building, Varick Street, east side, from King
to Houston Streets, seen across the excavation on the west side
for the United States Appraisers Stores Building.
December 7, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.
723764f-a.folder: Varick Street & King Street, Manhattan, NY

723766f-a.title: Manhattan: Varick Street - King Street
723766f-a.text:
Ecavation on the west side of Varick Street, from King to Houston
(formerly Hamnersley) Streets. The entire block, from Varick to
Huudson Streets, has been demolished for a new United States Appraiser's
Stores Building. Across this clearing may be seen the old houses
on the west side of Hudson Street, Nos. 363 to 385.
December 7, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.
723766f-a.folder: Varick Street & King Street, Manhattan, NY

723765f-a.title: Manhattan: Varick Street - King Street
723765f-a.text:
Varick Street, west side, from King to Clarkson Streets,
inclusive, showing the new Maltz Building and the clearing on
which the new United States Appraiser's Stores is being built.
February 12, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.

720727f-a.title: Manhattan: King Street - Varick Street
720727f-a.text:
29 King Street, North Side, between Varick and Congress
streets showing P.S. 8, built in 1886.
Board of Bducation, N.Y.C.
Neg. ~233

720729f-a.title: Manhattan: King Street - Varick Street
720729f-a.text:
King Street, north side, east from and including No. 49, east
of Varick Street. Public Cchool No. 8 occupies Nos. 35-27, inclusive.
The eastern end of King Street is at MacDougal Street, between
Houston and Prince Streets.
Eing Street was originally laid out as Hazard Street; it took its
present name in 1807, after an officer in the Revolutionary War, not
after His Majesty George III.
May 19, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
720729f-a.folder: King Street & Varick Street, Manhattan, NY

720728f-a.title: Manhattan: King Street - Varick Street
720728f-a.text:
44, 46, 48 to 54 King Street, south side, east of and towards
Varick Street. No. 46, the house with the dormer windows, is a
frame building faced with brick. In the center of the double house
48-50 is a carriage underpass to the rear of the building.
Adjoining No. 54 may be seen part of the Greybar-Varick Building
(1930), which replaced Nos. 56-58 and 60 King Street.
September, 1935.
dift of R. W. Hill.
